### 01_Load_sample_data

This script demonstrates the first step of the tutorial workflow: loading and integrating the sample datasets required for Sentinel-1 and LSTM-based water level estimation. 
The purpose of this step is to organize station metadata, ground-based water level observations, and preprocessed Sentinel-1 SAR-derived features into a consistent structure for subsequent analysis.

#### Files used in this step

- `Data/Sample_Data/Station_Sample.xlsx`  
  Contains monitoring station metadata, including station ID, station coordinates, river type, Sentinel-1 clipping range, clipped image size, and the pixel location corresponding to each station within the clipped Sentinel-1 image.

- `Data/Sample_Data/Water_level_sample.xlsx`  
  Contains sample ground-based water level observations, including station ID, observation date-time, and water level values.

#### Methodological purpose

The station metadata are used to define the spatial context of each monitoring site. This includes the geographic location of the station, the latitude and longitude range used to clip Sentinel-1 imagery, 
the size of the clipped image, and the row–column pixel index corresponding to the station location.

The water level observations are used as the ground-based target variable for the LSTM model. These records are organized by station ID and observation date-time.
The Sentinel-1 feature files provide preprocessed SAR-derived variables rather than original Sentinel-1 GRD imagery. The original SAR images are not included in this repository. 

Instead, these sample files represent feature values extracted after preprocessing steps such as thermal noise removal, radiometric calibration, speckle filtering, terrain correction, 
station-based clipping, and water body detection.

In this step, station ID is used to link station-based spatial information with the corresponding water level and Sentinel-1 feature records. 

Date-time information is then used to synchronize Sentinel-1 acquisition times with ground-based water level observations. 
Because Sentinel-1 observations are acquired less frequently than hourly water level measurements, the workflow illustrates how SAR acquisition times can be matched with corresponding or nearest available water level records.

The resulting station-specific dataset provides the basic time series structure required for the subsequent workflow, including Sentinel-1 feature preparation, water body detection evaluation, and LSTM-based water level estimation.
